<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910920-0008</DOCNO><DOCID>910920-0008.</DOCID><HL>   World Business (A Special Report)   ---   The Have-Nots</HL><DATE>09/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE R2</SO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)TRADE ISSUES (TRD)UNITED NATIONS (UNN)</NS><RE>AFRICA (AF)ZAIRE (CG)ETHIOPIA (ET)FAR EAST (FE)INDIA (II)PAKISTAN (PK)SOMALIA (SOM)SIERRA LEONE (SRL)UGANDA (UG)VIETNAM (VM)</RE><LP>   THE MONEY MAY be flowing more freely, but not everyone isgetting a piece of it.   A recent United Nations survey estimates that the poorestnations received 0.7% of direct foreign investment during thelatter half of the 1980s, way below the 1.5% of the firsthalf.</LP><TEXT>   The economic basket cases -- most of which are in Africa-- seem trapped in a vicious cycle of poverty: They havelittle money, so their economies never improve, so they don'tattract investment, so . . .   Uganda, Zaire, Ethiopia, Somalia and Sierra Leone all ratenear the top of most analysts' charts of high-risk countriesfor foreign investment. Not coincidentally, they are amongthe world's poorest. On the risk charts, these sub-Sarahannations rank below even the poorest and riskiest-investmentcountries in Asia -- India, Pakistan and Vietnam.   (See related story: &quot;Returning to the Third World:Emerging Nations Revive as Investment Hot Spots, but theRisks Are Hard to Assess&quot; -- WSJ Sept. 20, 1991)</TEXT></DOC>